\begin_layout Section
Model establishment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As problem set forth, the system contains five inputs and three outputs.
 For the number of output is less than input, it is a Underdetermined Blind
 Source Separation (UBSS) problem.
 We can solve this kind of problem using clustering method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The filter Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Simulating basilar membrane with Gammatone filter bank 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Human can use their basilar membrane to filter the noise and get the sound
 they want.
 In the case of pure tones input, when the frequency is high, the maximum
 amplitude of the sound wave occurs at the bottom of the basilar membrane;
 On the contray, it appears at the top.
 As the input sound wave is compound, basilar membrane can sperate those
 sound components with different frequency and amplitude, which will have
 the function of spectrum analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because basilar membrane have such function, we can use a series of filters
 to simulate the process mentioned above.
 The Commonly used filter banks include resonant filter bank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "C-lyon1988-analog"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Round-Exponential filter bank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "C-patterson-1986-auditory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Gammatone filter bank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "C-johannesma-1972-pre"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, ect.
 Because Gammatone filter bank can primely stimulate the physiological propertie
s by using less parameters and has a simple function of unit impulse response,
 so we apply Gammatone filter bank to our model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gammatone filter is defined by its function of unit impulse response in
 time domain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{i}(t)=At^{n-1}exp(-2\pi b_{i}t)cos(2\pi f_{i}+\phi_{i})u(t),t\geq0,1\leq i\leq N\label{eq:3.c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In formular 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.c"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 represents the gain of the filter, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 represents filter's center frequency, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 means the phase, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the order of the filter and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of Gammantone filter in the bank.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the decay factor of the filter, it determines the speed of impluse response'
s attenuation, and it can be defined as follow:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
bi=1.019ERB(f_{i})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $ERB(f_{i})$
\end_inset

 is the equivalent rectangular bandwidth of Gammantone filter, and it has
 the relationship with filter's center frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 as follow:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
ERB(f_{i})=24.7\times(4.37\times\frac{f_{i}}{1000}+1)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to simplify the model, we treat the phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=0$
\end_inset

, the filter's order 
\begin_inset Formula $n=4$
\end_inset

.
 Because all Gammatone filters use the same amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $A,$
\end_inset

so parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 will not affect the final result, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $A=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The nonelinearal compression of auditory system
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By searching for the literature, we find that auditory system has the characteri
stic of nonlinearity, which means the output power compression of high frequency
 signal differs from the low frequency one.
 This characteristic enhances anti-interference ability of auditory system
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "C-LiChaohui-2006-auditory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Scientists use 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 to analyze the nonlinearity of the auditory system, which is defined as
 below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda=\frac{10\lg(\frac{P_{o}}{P_{r}})}{10\lg(\frac{P_{i}}{P_{r}})}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value of parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 varies a lot in different literature, but there are two principles recognized
 by most scholars: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) it shows a strong compressing effect among signals of which frequency
 above 
\begin_inset Formula $1KHz$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is almost the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) if the signal's frequency is below 
\begin_inset Formula $1KHz$
\end_inset

, with its frequency decaying, compressing effect damps a lot.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use one of functions between 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and signal's freqency 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

obtainalbe in the literature satisfied those two priciples
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "C-HuFengson-2012-base-on"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which can be shown as the graph below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Refining the signal by FFT method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basilar membrane's refining and shielding process is similar to choose a
 group of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 in a certain range for the Gammatone filter bank.
 By selecting the center frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $1KHz-5KHz$
\end_inset

 uniformly, and calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, then we can get the sigals outputted by the auditory system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to make the sigals inputted more precise to the actual and apply
 to the computers, we need to discretize firstly.
 Then the discrete signals need to take the procedures of pre-emphasis,
 framing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $x(n)$
\end_inset

 is the signal before pre-emphasis, 
\begin_inset Formula $y(n)$
\end_inset

 is the signal after this process and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the shifting parameter.
 So pre-emphasis can be written as formula below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y(n)=x(n)-a\cdot x(n-1)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the process of framing, we use hamming window function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(n)$
\end_inset

 to mutiple 
\begin_inset Formula $y(n)$
\end_inset

 to get the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{w}(n)$
\end_inset

, which are as follow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{w}(n)=y(n)\cdot w(n)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(k)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{i}(k)$
\end_inset

 are the discrete spectrum of the signals 
\begin_inset Formula $y(n)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(n)$
\end_inset

 respectively after FFT, and then we can get the spectrum of discrete signals
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}(k)$
\end_inset

 outputted by the filter 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{i}(k)=(Y^{2}(k)H(k))^{\lambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M(k)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}M_{i}(k)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of the filter.
 Appearently, 
\begin_inset Formula $M(k)$
\end_inset

 is the whole power density spectrum of the output discrete signals.
 Using the inverse FFT, we can get the discrete output signal 
\begin_inset Formula $m(n)$
\end_inset

 in time domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The UBSS Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Mathematical expression of UBSS problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}^{t}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-dimensional column vector corresponding to the output of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 sensors at a given discrete time instant 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times T$
\end_inset

 matrix corresponding to the sensor data at all times 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,...,T$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\times T$
\end_inset

 matrix of underlying source signals and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

 mixing matrix.
 The problem of blind source separation consist of finding the solution
 to the following system of equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{X=AS}\label{eq:3.1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Because we have no information about the source signals or the mixing process,
 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 are unknown (We assume matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 is of full rank).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our step is to recover blind mixing matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 first and then estimate source signals matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The recovery of blind mixing matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can decompose Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{x^{\mathit{t}}}=\sum_{j=1}^{N}\mathbf{a^{\mathit{j}}}s_{j}^{t}\label{eq:3.2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We definite 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a^{\mathit{j}}}$
\end_inset

 is a column vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times N$
\end_inset

 mixing matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
 
