 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x^{\mathit{t}}}$
\end_inset

 is the output vector at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Following from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, if only one of the sources (say, source 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

) was different from zero, then all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x^{\mathit{t}}}$
\end_inset

 would be propertional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}^{i}$
\end_inset

 and all data points in mixture space would be aligned along the direction
 of this basis vector.
 When the sources are sparse, for a given data point 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, if one of the sources is significantly larger, the remaining ones are
 likely to be close to zero.
 Thus, the density of data in mixture space shows a clear tendency to cluster
 along the directions of the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}^{j}$
\end_inset

's.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Estimating the mixing matrix, then, consist of finding the directions of
 maximum data density.
 The directions is determined by column vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}^{j}$
\end_inset

 of mixing matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
 We can determine the directions of maximun data density by using k-means
 clustering algorithm.
 
\end_layout

