\begin_layout Subsubsection
The estimation of source signals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As it is an underdetermined system, Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are underdetermined equations.
 Even when mixing matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

is known, the solution of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is not unique.
 Our approach to sparse UBSS consist of finding the solution that minimizes
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 norm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case that blind mixing matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is known, the problem of inferring the source can be formulated independently
 for each data point 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{t}$
\end_inset

, leading to 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 tractable small problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{\mathbf{s}^{t}}\frac{1}{2\sigma^{2}}||\mathbf{A}\mathbf{s}^{t}-\mathbf{x}^{t}||^{2}+\sum_{j}\mid s_{j}^{t}\mid,\label{eq:3.3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1,...,T$
\end_inset

.
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is in case with additive Gaussian noise 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X=AS+V}$
\end_inset

, and assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is uniformly distributed.
 Variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the variance of the noise 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify the problem, we only consider the case in the absence of noise.
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be rewrited as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\min_{\mathbf{s}^{t}}\sum_{j}\mid s_{j}^{t}\mid\label{eq:3.4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s.t\quad As^{\mathit{t}}=x^{\mathit{t}}\qquad t=1,...,T
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3.4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is equivalent to minimizing the 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{t}$
\end_inset

.
 It is obviously to find that if the original signals are sparser, the the
 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

 norm of 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{t}$
\end_inset

 will be smaller.
 We can solve this problem by using linear programming algorithm.
 
\end_layout

